04405nam a22005175i 9780226240244DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226240244  a(DE-B1597)524651  a(OCoLC)912422258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDS435.7.S26bC53 2016 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a907.2022231 aChakrabarty, Dipesh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Calling of History :bSir Jadunath Sarkar and His Empire of Truth /cDipesh Chakrabarty. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b11 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Popular Origins of Academic History -- t2. Debating Research -- t3. Hunters and Gatherers of Historical Documents -- t4. The Politics of “Unquestionable” Facts -- t5. The Statesman as Hero: An Imperial Aesthetic for a National History -- t6. Between Providence and Character: The Historian Himself -- t7. Archiving the Nation: Sarkar’s Fall from Grace -- t8. The Author and the Historian: A Conversational Reverie -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA leading scholar in early twentieth-century India, Sir Jadunath Sarkar (1870–1958) was knighted in 1929 and became the first Indian historian to gain honorary membership in the American Historical Association. By the end of his lifetime, however, he had been marginalized by the Indian history establishment, as postcolonial historians embraced alternative approaches in the name of democracy and anti-colonialism. The Calling of History examines Sarkar’s career—and poignant obsolescence—as a way into larger questions about the discipline of history and its public life. Through close readings of more than twelve hundred letters to and from Sarkar along with other archival documents, Dipesh Chakrabarty demonstrates that historians in colonial India formulated the basic concepts and practices of the field via vigorous—and at times bitter and hurtful—debates in the public sphere. He furthermore shows that because of its non-technical nature, the discipline as a whole remains susceptible to pressure from both the public and the academy even today. Methodological debates and the changing reputations of scholars like Sarkar, he argues, must therefore be understood within the specific contexts in which particular histories are written. Insightful and with far-reaching implications for all historians, The Calling of History offers a valuable look at the double life of history and how tensions between its public and private sides played out in a major scholar’s career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistorianszIndia. 0aHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acivilizations, 20th century, india, american historical association, sir jadunath sarkar, historian, postcolonial, postcolonialism, marginalization, public life, biography, academy, mughal dynasty, history of aurangzib, historiography, south asia, marginalized, colony, colonial, british empire, imperialism, context, understanding, career, scholarship, scholarly work.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022610044940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226240244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226240244/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles